	<h2>D&acirc;l is for Dinar</h2>



<p class="illo"><img src="../_img/dal2.png" width="200" align="right" style="margin-right:-80px" /></p>
<p>D&acirc;l is the fourth basic shape. We started with the shape of Alif (population one). Ba, with that simple plate shape, plus dots, gave us the second and least interesting of the shapes. J&icirc;m was the mold for three or four additional letters. The D&acirc;l shape marks the end of a series (with one companion letter to follow). The four shapes in sequence spell <em>abjad</em>. &#1575;&#1576;&#1580;&#1583;. ) .&#1583; .&#1580; .&#1576; .&#1575;)</p>
<p>D&acirc;l in its simplest form is just two lines which splay out leftward from a point usually at the base line. In calligraphy the upper line can be thick or thin, drawn with the full width of the reed&rsquo;s edge, but it is almost always nearly upright, leaning at perhaps the 11:00 position. The lower line ramps down to the left, usually at a slight angle, perhaps 8:00.&nbsp; From the Nabataean predecessor, an inverted L, D&acirc;l has rotated not quite 180 degrees clockwise. More schematically, we can imagine it as simply two thirds of an equilateral triangle with the left side missing. Its Greek counterpart, Delta, adds the third side, to form the complete triangle.</p>
<p>Perhaps because it is a simple letter, in calligraphy there is room for considerable variation. It may curl up as it tapers. You may see the lower mandible almost join the upper one. There are lengthened versions which allow them to stretch out left in long, straight parallel lines.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p>Like Alif (and like the next four letters), it connects only on the right, so that even when it occurs in the middle of a word it seems to come to a stop. It always looks as if it could be the end of a word. (Often, it is: in Persian, D&acirc;l is a common suffix for third-person singular verbs &mdash; as a D suffix in English marks the third-person in our past tense verbs.) So all three forms of D&acirc;l &mdash; initial, medial and terminal &mdash; are identical. It takes no particular effort to learn. In the Iranian first-year primary school textbook, at least the one I have, you learn Alif and Ba first of course, which allows you to spell <em>B&acirc;b&acirc;</em>, father, and <em>&acirc;b</em>, water. Going out of sequence, the next letter the book presents is D&acirc;l, which allows you to spell <em>d&acirc;d</em>, &ldquo;gave.&rdquo; The first full sentence of the text book is <strong>&#1576;&#1575;&#1576;&#1575; &#1570;&#1576; &#1583;&#1575;&#1583;</strong>&ldquo;B&acirc;b&acirc; &acirc;b d&acirc;d,&rdquo; with an illustration of a rural scene where a father in traditional clothes is kneeling to offer a bowl of water to a little girl. My example is from the Shah&rsquo;s day. You go with what you have.</p>
<p class="illo"><img src="../_img/dal3.png" width="300" align="right" style="margin-right:-80px" /></p>
<p>A <em>dab&icirc;r</em> in Persian is a teacher. A <em>dab&icirc;rest&acirc;n</em> is a high school. (A <em>dabir</em> is also a secretary, as in secretary of state. Also, in Persian, the recording angel.) <em>D&acirc;nestan</em> in Persian is &ldquo;to know.&rdquo; <em>D&acirc;nesh</em> in Persian is knowledge, learning, science. A <em>d&acirc;neshg&acirc;h </em>is a university. A <em>d&acirc;nesh&acirc;muz</em> is a student. A <em>d&acirc;neshvar</em> is a scientist.</p>
<p><em>Dars</em> is study, education, a lesson, in both Arabic, Persian and Turkish (where it is spelled <em>ders</em> with an E). The Arabic D-R-S is a prolific stem; <em>tadr&icirc;s</em> is teaching, a <em>mudarris</em> is a teacher. A school is a <em>madrasa</em>. In Hebrew, <em>midrash</em> (commentary, interpretation) is a cognate, in fact more or less the same word. <em>Madrasa</em> is often the term for a religious school, but just as often it is the other kind, where secular knowledge of the sublunary world, the <em>duny&acirc;</em>, is the dominant subject.</p>
<p class="illo"><img src="../_img/dal4.png" width="200" align="right" style="margin-right:-80px" /></p>
<p>The stem D-KH-L in Arabic generates verbs and nouns with a <em>duny&acirc;</em> of meanings. (<em>Duny&acirc;</em> can function as a counter word, &ldquo;a world of meanings.&rdquo;) All of them circle around ideas of entering. A <em>madkhal</em> is a hallway or lobby, also a highway leading into a big city. <em>D&acirc;khil&icirc;</em> is &ldquo;inward&rdquo; or inside.&rdquo;<em> Dakhl</em> is income.<em> Madkh&ucirc;l </em>means diseased, abnormal. A <em>dakh&ucirc;l&icirc;ya</em> is an entrance fee. <em>Dakh&icirc;l </em>is the term for a loan word.&nbsp; A word you are likely to see frequently in signs (the counterpart of <em>khur&ucirc;j</em>, &ldquo;exit&rdquo;) is <em>dukh&ucirc;l</em>, &ldquo;entrance.&rdquo;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p>The entrance to a work of literature in Persian is a <em>d&icirc;b&acirc;cheh</em>, a preface or foreword. With that CH sound it appears to be as Persian as you can get, but evidence suggests that it comes from Arabic <em>d&icirc;b&acirc;ja</em>, &ldquo;brocade,&rdquo; which also means elegance, ornament, or the opening of a poem.</p>
<p>Among the most ubiquitous words in Persian poetry are <em>del</em> (&ldquo;heart&rdquo; or &ldquo;seat of the emotions&rdquo;), <em>dam</em> (&ldquo;breath&rdquo;) and <em>dust</em> (pronounced &ldquo;doost&rdquo;), &ldquo;friend.&rdquo; <em>Dust</em>, in poetry, is not always a word of intimacy. The <em>dust</em> is just as frequently a distant and unattainable presence, whose unattainable nature is a source of <em>dard</em>, &ldquo;pain.&rdquo;</p>
<p class="illo"><img src="../_img/dal5.png" width="300" align="right" style="margin-right:-80px" /></p>
<p>The opposite of <em>dust </em>is another D&acirc;l word, <em>doshman</em>, &ldquo;enemy.&rdquo; <em>Doshman</em> is one of those words whose stems can be traced way back. The <em>dosh</em>- part can be identified in the Indo-European root <em>dus</em>- (bad, evil). The same suffix is visible in Persian <em>doshv&acirc;r</em>, &ldquo;difficult,&rdquo; and <em>doshn&acirc;m</em> &ldquo;swearing.&rdquo;) The <em>dosh</em> part exists further west in Greek &delta;&upsilon;&sigma;- which gives us English <em>dys</em>-, as in &ldquo;dystrophy,&rdquo; &ldquo;dysfunctional,&rdquo; or &ldquo;dyslexic.&rdquo; In Greek, the word <em>doshman</em> has a close cognate: &delta;&upsilon;&sigma;&mu;&eta;&nu;&iota;&sigma;/<em>d&uacute;sm&ecirc;nis</em>, &ldquo;wrathful.&rdquo; <em>Dust </em>and <em>doshman</em> are often a symmetrical pair. The proverb says, in Persian, &ldquo;<em>doshman-e doshman-at dust-at ast</em>.&rdquo; Your enemy&rsquo;s enemy is your friend. Possibly right, definitely symmetrical.</p>
<p>The Arabic stem D-J-L means to deceive. <em>Dajl</em> is deceit, trickery, a swindle. Dajj&acirc;l doesn&rsquo;t occur in the Qur&rsquo;an, but it has become a popular item in theology. In an agent form, Dajj&acirc;l, an impostor, is a particular deceiver, the enemy of mankind, the equivalent of what in Christianity is called the anti-Christ. He will show up at the end of times, riding a donkey, stopping at one city after another to preach. The same figure exists in Christian tradition. It even enters the Chronicles of Narnia, in <em>The Last Battle</em>.&nbsp;</p>
<h3>Percussion</h3>
<p>Among the words which tip us off to the status of Persian as an Indo-European language, like English, are <em>dokhtar</em> (daughter and young woman), <em>dar</em> (door) and <em>dand&acirc;n</em> (tooth). <em>Dand&acirc;n</em> has a cognate in the word &ldquo;dental&rdquo; (like French <em>dent </em>or Italian <em>dente</em>, as in <em>al dente</em>). A dental consonant (Persian <em>dand&acirc;l&icirc;</em>) is a sound in which the tongue touches the teeth (like the sound of D&acirc;l). We may hear it as a letter appropriate to things knocking against one another, phonological percussion. In Arabic, <em>darabukka </em>or <em>dirbakka</em> is a one of those drums with a narrowing conical shape to fit under the player&rsquo;s arm. A <em>dombak</em> (or <em>tombak</em>) is roughly the same thing in Persian. A <em>daff</em> is a tambourine. The Arabic verb <em>dabaka</em> is to stamp the feet. The <em>dabka</em> is a dance (described as a &ldquo;line dance&rdquo; by Wikipedia). The Arabic verb <em>dabdaba</em> is to step, clomp or stomp. The noun <em>daqqa </em>means the sound of banging, knocking, hammering or thumping. <em>Dang</em> in Persian is a ringing sound, &ldquo;clang&rdquo; or &ldquo;ding.&rdquo;</p>
<p>In English, for some reason D plays a smaller role in the vocabulary of onomatopoeia. We have &ldquo;ding&rdquo; and &ldquo;ding dong,&rdquo; but the percussive preference in English is for B: Bang, boom, blam, bonk, boing and (if we take ka- as a prefix), kablooey. But English may be in the minority. Certainly a lot of languages opt for D. &ldquo;Da&rdquo; is the sound of thunder in Sanskrit (as in thunder words <em>datta</em>, <em>dayaddhvam</em>, <em>damyata</em>, which we learn from the endnotes to Eliot&rsquo;s &ldquo;Waste Land&rdquo;). In the fictional Orkan language, devised for a vintage board game called Warhammer 40,000 (b. 1987), the word &ldquo;dakka&rdquo; is the sound of automatic gun-fire. (&ldquo;More dakka,&rdquo; I&rsquo;m told, is a battle cry.) &ldquo;Dakka,&rdquo; they say, is as fundamental to the game as <em>dust </em>and <em>del</em> are to Persian poetry. The link between the D sound and percussion, English notwithstanding, may be so widespread that it overflows human language.</p>
<h3>Geography</h3>
<p><em>Darreh</em> in Persian means a valley. The village of Darra Adam Kel (the <em>darreh</em> of the &Acirc;damkhel tribe) in northwestern Pakistan is famous for handmade weapons of all kinds (including both fake Kalashnikoffs and American M16s). Their cottage industries are said to have supplied Afghan opposition movements since the Soviet invasion. The legal ramifications have not been a problem, since it is famous as a region where government control doesn&rsquo;t reach. It has enjoyed a flourishing economy until recently, since (as I write) government power is said to have begun extending into the tribal areas.</p>
<p>Place names are often enough made from common nouns, like<em> darreh</em> or <em>darra</em>. In Turkish a <em>d&acirc;gh</em> is a mountain. (In Persian and in Arabic what looks like the same word means &ldquo;hot,&rdquo; also a scar or a brand. From &ldquo;brand&rdquo; to &ldquo;mountain.&rdquo; In Urdu it is a stain or spot: there must be some logic there.) The land of mountains is Dagestan, formerly a Soviet Socialist Republic, which extends from the Caucasus mountains to the west coast of the Caspian Sea. The name of its capital, Derbent, comes from Persian <em>dar-band</em>, which means among other things a narrow mountain pass. The massive Steingass dictionary lists as one of a <em>duny&acirc; </em>of meanings &ldquo;a place where there is good wine.&rdquo;</p>
<p>There is a variety of wine from eastern Bulgaria called Dimiat, which may be indigenous to the Black Sea coast, but there is an alternative history that says that the grape was first grown near a port city in the Nile Delta named Dumy&acirc;&#7789;. The name Dumy&acirc;&#7789; traces back through Coptic to archaic Egyptian &ldquo;Tamiat,&rdquo; the city we now call, in a European sounding variant, Damietta. It has probably produced more history than wine: during the Crusades it was a popular place for European forces to attack first, on their way down the Nile to establish a base of operations. They didn&rsquo;t always make it. Today the dominant industry is furniture.</p>
<p>Sonnet 130 is the one where Shakespeare takes a series of extravagant comparisons traditional in love poetry and denies them. (&ldquo;My mistress&rsquo;s eyes are nothing like the sun&rdquo;). The point is a kind of anti-courtly manifesto that human beings are not really much like the poems of praise which describe them. When the comparison comes to flowers, he adds &ldquo;I have seen roses damask&rsquo;d, white and red / but no such roses see I in her cheeks.&rdquo; The roses he imagines have wavy patterns which connect us eastward across the sea (D&acirc;l word <em>dary&acirc;</em>) to Damascus. The steel of Damascus was forged of two separate metals and twisted in the forging process, a process which leaves swirling marks and for some reason makes it particularly hard to break. The products of Damascus steel were weapons, but the wavy patterns of the metal became proverbial simply for their appearance, applicable to flowers, patterns on cloth, and ornaments in poetry.&nbsp;</p>
