<h3>The Government</h3>
<p>D&acirc;l words dominate the vocabulary of governance. In Persian the <em>darb&acirc;r</em> is the court. A <em>d&acirc;d-gah</em> is a court in the other sense, as in a courtroom &mdash; <em>d&acirc;d</em> meaning not just &ldquo;gave&rdquo; but also &ldquo;justice.&rdquo; A <em>dast&ucirc;r </em>(&#1583;&#1587;&#1578;&#1608;&#1585;) in Persian is a command or an order. As a loan word in Arabic it has changed its voweling and become <em>dust&ucirc;r</em> (plural <em>das&acirc;t&icirc;r</em> / &#1583;&#1587;&#1575;&#1578;&#1740;&#1585;), constitution.</p>
<p>A <em>daftar</em> is in common speech a notebook or diary, but a <em>daftar </em>is also an office. It also suggests the authority of governments: a ledger, registry or account book. Though it has an Arabic plural (<em>daf&acirc;tir</em> / &#1583;&#1601;&#1575;&#1578;&#1585;), it comes originally from Greek (<em>difth&eacute;ra / </em>&delta;&iota;&phi;&theta;&epsilon;&rho;&alpha;, the word for leather). Greek <em>kh&aacute;rtes</em> / &chi;&alpha;&rho;&tau;&eta;&sigmaf; (as in English &ldquo;charter&rdquo; or Magna charta) means roughly the same thing; Greek <em>kh&aacute;rtes</em> evolves into Arabic <em>qirt&acirc;s </em>, &#1602;&#1585;&#1591;&#1575;&#1587;, &ldquo;parchment,&rdquo; i.e. a surface for writing, which in the Qur&rsquo;&acirc;n is opposed to the spoken word. Even if the revelation of the Qur&rsquo;&acirc;n had come down in written form, it says in Surat al-A&lsquo;n&acirc;m, even if it had come to humans inscribed on <em>qirt&acirc;s</em>, instead of spoken by a messenger, unbelievers would still find a way to deny it &ndash; Q 6.7)&nbsp;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Divan&rdquo; is one of those words which does a lot of work in English (a backless couch, a tribunal, a government bureau, the complete works of a poet, or &ldquo;a coffee house or smoking lounge with divans&rdquo; &ndash;<em> American Heritage Dictionary</em>). The Arabic source works just as hard. Originally from an Arabic stem (D&ndash;W&ndash;N, to write down, record) it has put down roots in Persian and Turkish, where it is used to designate the account books of the treasury. It came into French as the word for a customs office, <em>douane</em>, Italian <em>dogana</em>.</p>
<p>A <em>d&acirc;r</em> (often translated &ldquo;abode&rdquo;) can be a stopping place where a tribe might camp, a temporary settlement. In pre-Islamic poetry it is the encampment of a nomadic community, a cluster of tents, but it can also be a building. It can be the <em>d&acirc;r</em> of the <em>d&acirc;r al-sal&acirc;m</em>, The House of Peace, a term for heaven. Dar es Salaam, the capital of Tanzania, is the same phrase. In an Arabic newspaper, the American White House is translated literally as Al-D&acirc;r al-bay&#7693;&acirc;&rsquo;. Casablanca, the city (<em>casa</em>, house, plus <em>blanca</em>, &ldquo;white&rdquo;) is the same phrase: <em>Al-D&acirc;r al-bay&#7693;&acirc;&rsquo;</em>. <em>D&acirc;r al-shif&acirc;&rsquo;</em>, house of healing, is a term for a hospital. <em>D&acirc;r al-kutub </em>is a library. D&acirc;r has come to be a signifier of stability wherever it appears.</p>
<p>The stem of D&acirc;r, D-W-R, has as its key meaning to revolve or turn. A Turkish equivalent is D&acirc;l verb <em>d&ouml;nmek</em>, &ldquo;to revolve,&rdquo; stem of <em>d&ouml;ner</em>, turning, revolving, thus <em>d&ouml;ner kebap</em> (English &ldquo;doner kebab&rdquo;), which is roasted on a rotating spit. D-W-R generates <em>d&acirc;&rsquo;ira</em>, a circle. An <em>id&acirc;ra</em> is both the act of circling and a government office, department, bureau or administration. (There must be some logic there.) A <em>mud&icirc;r</em> is a director or manager. <em>Mud&acirc;r </em>means an orbit.</p>
<p>A <em>dubb</em> is a bear. <em>Al-dubb al-asghar</em> is the little bear. The <em>qutb,</em> the pivot around which everything turns is the tip of its tail (Persian <em>donb&acirc;leh</em>).</p>
<p>There are other celestial animals. A <em>dajj&acirc;j </em>is a chicken; a <em>dajj&acirc;ja</em> is a hen, the term for the constellation we know as Cygnus. (The name <em>Dajj&acirc;ja</em> becomes, as it travels west, a testament to imaginative transcription: Cygnus is Adigeghe, Degige and Adigagato). It&rsquo;s easier to see as a swan than a hen. That cross shape (Cygnus&rsquo;s alternate name is the Northern Cross) makes it one of the easiest constellations to pick out (along with the two dippers and the three stars of Orion&rsquo;s belt). We learn to see it as a swan because the long side of the cross is like a swan&rsquo;s long neck, the short side the back end, marked by its brightest star, Deneb in English, originally Dhanab, the &ldquo;tail.&rdquo; Granted, it takes a little imagination to impose a bird shape of any kind on a simple cross. But then, if we didn&rsquo;t have constellations to domesticate them, it would have been much harder to find names for individual stars. If we had star names but no constellations to organize them the sky would seem a lot more chaotic and mysterious. Their circling would seem an aimless round.</p>
