<h3>The Economy</h3>
<p><em>Darv&icirc;sh </em>(accent on the second syllable), a Persian term familiar in Turkish (<em>dervi≈ü</em>) and Arabic (<em>darw&icirc;sh</em>), has also traveled to English in the form of &ldquo;dervish&rdquo; (accent on the first). We visualize the <em>darv&icirc;sh </em>as a wandering mendicant. The beggar&rsquo;s bowl (<em>kashk&ucirc;l</em>) is the time-honored accoutrement. Folklore sees the dervish as a wanderer even if they live in one place, in search of something they cannot yet see, hoping to track down the ultimate security. (One meaning of &ldquo;darv&icirc;sh&rdquo; is a Sufi, a wanderer seeking a spiritual goal.)</p>
<p>The word &ldquo;dervish,&rdquo; Henry Yule tells us, &ldquo;is hardly used now among Anglo-Indians, <em>faq&icirc;r</em> having taken its place.&rdquo; <em>Faq&icirc;r</em> is a term (in Arabic, Persian and Turkish) meaning &ldquo;poor.&rdquo; It is also used for a religious ascetic, either Moslem or Hindu. Often enough it is used as a synonym for <em>darv&icirc;sh</em>. When we see the English transcription &ldquo;fakir&rdquo; we may want to put the accent on the first syllable and make it sound like &ldquo;faker.&rdquo; Actually, both, <em>darv&icirc;sh</em> and <em>faq&icirc;r</em>, can be considered low-life. In either case, sincere or fake, a <em>darv&icirc;sh</em> is, by tradition, poor.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p>A quatrain in Persian which someone taught me long ago (driving past a graveyard in Kermanshah), has <em>darv&icirc;sh</em> as the rhyming word:&nbsp;</p>
