<p>Dal word <em>dawlatmand </em>is a rich man, from Arabic <em>dawla</em>, wealth, power. The stem D-W-L, to alternate, take turns (because wealth is fleeting?). <em>Dawla</em> (in Persian <em>dowlat</em>, with the accent on the second syllable) is also the word for government. In its plural form, <em>duwal</em>, it is audible in <em>Al-Duwal al-muttahida</em>, United Nations. It is the Dawla of <em>D&acirc;&lsquo;ish</em>, i.e. the Arabic abbreviation for <strong><em>D</em></strong><em>awlat al-</em><strong><em>i</em></strong><em>slamiyya f&icirc;-l-</em><strong><em>&lsquo;I</em></strong><em>r&acirc;q wa al-</em><strong><em>Sh</em></strong><em>&acirc;m </em>&mdash; D&acirc;l-Alif-&lsquo;Ayn-Sh) also called I.S.I.S.<strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>
<h3>Money</h3>
<p>Freud&rsquo;s <em>Beyond the Pleasure Principle </em>(1921), one of those speculative inquiries which he began to launch late in his career, ends with two lines of poetry from a German poem no longer famous. Freud cites it to confess that he is probing beyond what he feels he can prove. It suggests that his argument has been halting and tentative:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><em>Was man nicht erfliegen kann, muss man erhinken,<br /></em><em>. . .<br /></em><em>Die Schrift sagt, es ist keine S&uuml;nde zu hinken</em></p>
<p>[In C.J.M. Hubback&rsquo;s translation &ldquo;Whither we may not fly, we must go limping./ The scripture sayeth that limping is no sin.&rdquo; ]&nbsp;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Freud identifies his source as &ldquo;Ein Dichter (R&uuml;ckert in den Makamen des Hariri).&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
<p>R&uuml;ckert is Friedrich R&uuml;ckert, who had the distinction of being both a poet and a specialist in languages. His translation (1826) of Al-&#7716;ar&icirc;r&icirc;&rsquo;s 13th-century <em>Maq&acirc;m&acirc;t </em>(German transcription <em>Makamen</em>) is famous in German, not just as an academic exercise (it&rsquo;s not an easy text), but as poetry. Freud&rsquo;s citation doesn&rsquo;t suggest something exotic. It has an effect like what a quotation from FitzGerald&rsquo;s translations of Omar Khayyam would convey in English, a little exotic but recognizable and familiar.&nbsp;</p>
<p>A <em>maq&acirc;m</em> is a spot, a location, a locality, a stopping place. The plural, <em>Maq&acirc;m&acirc;t</em>, is the name of a genre of writing (devised by Bad&icirc;&lsquo; al-Zam&acirc;n al-Hamad&acirc;ni in the 10th century) in which a character travels across the Arab world. Everywhere he stops, in each <em>maqam</em>, there is a little narrative of what he encountered there. What he encounters at every stop is pretty much the same: he regularly meets a trickster figure, usually a beggar, usually in disguise, always a great orator and poet.</p>
<p>Al-&#7716;ar&icirc;r&icirc; of Basra, writing in the early 12th century is, after Bad&icirc;&lsquo; al-Zam&acirc;n al-Hamad&acirc;n&icirc;, the most famous writer of <em>maq&acirc;m&acirc;t</em>. Maybe Al-&#7716;ar&icirc;r&icirc;&rsquo;s version is competition with his predecessor or maybe it&rsquo;s something more like an homage. (Al-Har&icirc;r&icirc;&rsquo;s introduction to his <em>maq&acirc;m&acirc;t</em> says, in Thomas Chenerey&rsquo;s 1867 translation &ldquo;Bad&icirc;&lsquo;. . . is a mighty passer of goals, a worker of wonders, adding &ldquo;he who assays after him to the composition of the Assembly [<em>maq&acirc;ma</em>] . . . does but scoop up his overflow&rdquo; &ndash; p. 106.) There was a lot of overflow. The form persisted, recognizable, until the 20th century. In al-&#7716;ar&icirc;r&icirc;&rsquo;s <em>Maq&acirc;m&acirc;t</em>, &Icirc;s&acirc; ibn Hish&acirc;m is the narrator; the trickster is Ab&ucirc; Zayd of Ser&ucirc;j. In the third <em>maq&acirc;ma</em> we recognize the pattern: &ldquo;Al-&#7716;&acirc;rith, son of Hamm&acirc;m, related: &lsquo;I was set with some comrades in a company&hellip;&rdquo; (117).&nbsp; They begin to recite poems and tell each other stories, when a beggar comes by, limping. Al-&#7716;&acirc;rith offers to give him a coin if he praises it with sufficient eloquence. The stranger improvises a poem about money and gold: &ldquo;The yellow one&rdquo; is a great voyager and tales about it spread abroad. Everyone loves the yellow one. It solves a host of problems (it gives power to rulers, solaces the grieving, gives peace to the angry, releases the prisoner&hellip;).&nbsp; If it weren&rsquo;t for God, money would seem invincible.</p>
<p class="illo"><img src="../_img/dal11.png" width="300" align="right" style="margin-right:-80px" /></p>
<p>The poem impresses Al-&#7716;&acirc;rith so much that he promises another coin, on the condition that the beggar improvise a second poem arguing the contrary. No problem. &ldquo;It has two faces, like a liar, and it&rsquo;s a cause of sin. If only coins didn&rsquo;t exist the thief would not have nothing to do, and would not end up being punished. Cowards could walk at night without fear. It abandons you like a runaway slave, we should throw it away from the top of a mountain . . .&rdquo; Al-&#7716;&acirc;rith gives the beggar the second coin, and, as the beggar begins to leave, he recognizes him as his friend Ab&ucirc; Zayd. But why is he limping? The <em>maq&acirc;ma</em> closes with Ab&ucirc; Zayd&rsquo;s explanation. It&rsquo;s useful to evoke sympathy. He&rsquo;s not limping because he wants to, just <em>aqr&acirc;&lsquo; b&acirc;b al-faraj</em>, to knock on the door of happiness, if the two coins can be called happiness.</p>
<p>A quote from Al-&#7716;ar&icirc;r&icirc; may be an inappropriate way for Freud to sum up his own book. The situation of a writer like Freud going beyond what he can prove, haltingly, walking unsteadily into a provisional argument, could certainly be something like limping, but it doesn&rsquo;t really match the case of Ab&ucirc; Zayd. Ab&ucirc; Zayd is only pretending to be lame. (He walks around just fine in later episodes.) Perhaps Freud felt that in <em>Beyond the Pleasure Principle</em> he wasn&rsquo;t lame either: his thesis was actually airtight and able-bodied, just not subject to proof &mdash; in which case he too is only pretending to limp. It&rsquo;s possible.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p>The coin (or pair of coins) Al-&#7716;&acirc;rith offers to Ab&ucirc; Zayd is a <em>d&icirc;n&acirc;r</em>.&#1583;&#1740;&#1606;&#1575;&#1585;. It is a word of some antiquity. It turns up in the Qur&rsquo;&acirc;n as a generic term for a coin (Q 3.75). It traces back to the Roman <em>denarius</em>. The Latin word <em>denarius</em> in the Vulgate (translating Greek <em>n&oacute;misma</em>) is translated in the King James Bible as &ldquo;penny&rdquo; (Matthew 22.19). The British abbreviation for a penny is still the letter D, D for <em>denarius</em>. (Indeed there are still nine countries which use the name <em>dinar</em> for their own currency. I looked it up.) The <em>dirham</em> (from Greek <em>drakhm&eacute;</em>), has a comparable linguistic history. It passed from Greek to Latin, and it was also absorbed into Arabic early. Joseph&rsquo;s brothers in the twelfth Sura sell him for a few dirhams (&#1583;&#1585;&#1575;&#1607;&#1605;, <em>dar&acirc;him</em>,12.20). In Kuwait, today, a <em>dirham</em> still exists. (It&rsquo;s a tenth of a <em>dinar</em>.)</p>
<p>A <em>d&icirc;n&acirc;r </em>was evidently a coin of substantial value for Ab&ucirc; Zayd, but it continued to lose value as time went by. In 1886 Henry Yule describes its decline vividly: &ldquo;The <em>d&icirc;n&acirc;r</em> in modern Persia is a very small imaginary coin, of which 10,000 make a tomaun.&rdquo; (By coincidence, &ldquo;toman&rdquo; stems from a Mongol word for the number 10,000.) Currently, as I write, in Iran there are 3,400 Iranian tomans to the dollar. (I&rsquo;m writing a later draft now; the value has sunk to 4,202.7 per dollar.) The particular coins which Ab&ucirc; Zayd was granted would be worth a great deal today, as collector&rsquo;s items, if we had the originals, but that would be for their historical value, not according to the official exchange rate. Adjusted for inflation it would be worth very little.</p>
<h3>Dimna</h3>
<p>We know the great story collection <em>Kalila wa Dimna</em> from the version translated elegantly into Arabic by Ibn-Muqaffa&lsquo; in the eighth century. It became a model of style (though the stories would be just as entertaining without the elegance). His source was evidently a version (now lost) in Pahlavi, the language of pre-Islamic Iran. This in turn traces further back to the (still extant) Sanskrit <em>Panchatantra.</em> The title characters in Arabic, the two jackals Dimna and Kalila, can be recognized as counterparts of two characters from the Sanskrit original, Damana and Karata, though the names have taken new forms. I am told that Karata in Sanskrit, the name of the reasonable jackal (Kal&icirc;l&acirc; in Arabic), meant "a crude, unbelieving, lowly" person. The name Kal&icirc;l&acirc; is a phonetic equivalent of the Sanskrit name, more or less. Damanaka, the name of the other jackal, our villain, means in Sanskrit someone who &ldquo;subdues, controls, punishes." Proper names, strictly speaking, do not need to be translated, but his Arabic name Dimna, counterpart of Damanaka, counts as a translation as well as a name, a name with a meaning in Arabic too. The verbal stem in Arabic for Dimna is D-M-N, to fertilize. <em>Dimna </em>means &ldquo;dung.&rdquo; So Ibn Muqaffa&lsquo; tips us off Dimna&rsquo;s character by the time we&rsquo;ve read the title.</p>
<p>There is a miniature, seven-word lexicon by Jaroslav Stetkevych of key words in early Arabic poetry (Stetkevych, 58-129). Those seven words are enough to generate a world of commentary. (The essay is 71 pages long.) His specific topic is the <em>na&#7779;&icirc;b</em>, the stylized opening scene of the pre-Islamic ode. (There are usually considered to be two others, a praise of the poet&rsquo;s horse or camel and then a panegyric.) Traditionally, in the <em>na&#7779;&icirc;b</em>, the poet speaks in the first person as a heroic figure, radiating the heroism of an outsider, a loner riding outside the security of a tribe. The traditional scene is a deserted place where a tribe has once camped. The narrator lingers to look. A lover from the past belongs to that tribe, and the traces they left behind are now as close to her as he will get.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s a melancholy scene, but also a demonstration of the poet&rsquo;s acuity &mdash; not just as a poet, but as an observer, since he&rsquo;s reading the traces as an intermediary between him and the past. He&rsquo;s a figure like a tracker in western terms, the pathfinder who reads the signs, unnoticed by others, in order to find his way. In the traditional <em>nas&icirc;b</em> the poet already knows where he is. He just wishes he were further back in time, back when the woman he is longing for was still there.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The seven words of Stetkevych&rsquo;s lexicon are <em>tal&acirc;l</em> (pl. <em>itl&acirc;l</em>, ruins), <em>nu&rsquo;y</em>, a trench, <em>rab&lsquo;</em>, a spot where the tribe stops in springtime, <em>su&rsquo;&acirc;l</em>, question, <em>ath&acirc;f&icirc;</em>, hearth stones, and two D&acirc;l words: <em>d&acirc;r</em>, a word we know already, and <em>dimna</em>.&nbsp; <em>Dimna</em> is an unpromising word for an erotic poem, dung being, after all, dung, but Stetkevych demonstrates that poet after poet has described the droppings of the tribe&rsquo;s animals in positive terms, without irony, as a text to be read, as in the opening of a poem by the pre-Islamic poet &lsquo;Ab&icirc;d ibn a-Abras:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><em>Li man </em><strong><em>dimnatun </em></strong><em>aqwat bi harrati Darghad&icirc;<br /></em><em>tal&ucirc;hu ka &lsquo;unw&acirc;ni l-kit&acirc;bi l-muaddad&icirc;?</em><em>&nbsp;</em></p>
<p>[Whose <em>dimna</em> is this that lies deserted / at the black basalt track of Darghad (a place name) / emerging like a book&rsquo;s border lettering redrawn? &ndash; tr. Stetkevych, p. 78]</p>
</blockquote>
<p>In the <em>nas&icirc;b</em> of another poet (Lab&icirc;d) the scene of the droppings is described explicitly as a parchment (<em>&#7779;a&#7717;&acirc;&rsquo;if</em>) with writing. They are a mark of separation but they&rsquo;re the only connection he still has.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s a kind of writing, definitely not a love letter, but a testimony of daily life, a few steps beyond Shakespeare&rsquo;s Sonnet 130.</p>

